{"type":"assistant","message":{"model":"claude-sonnet-4-6","id":"msg_01QpLXJmYYofEXE3EJtiwwCS","type":"message","role":"assistant","content":[{"type":"thinking","thinking":"The issue is that `/etc/ingress-controller/telemetry/` is on a read-only filesystem. The controller tries to write the TOML file at startup (it wants to generate/write it), but since I've mounted a ConfigMap there, the filesystem is read-only and it can't write to it.\n\nThe error is: `open /etc/ingress-controller/telemetry/opentelemetry.toml: read-only file system`\n\nThis means the ingress-nginx controller tries to WRITE the TOML file at startup. My ConfigMap mount makes it read-only, which prevents the write.\nI need to try a different approach. I could mount the ConfigMap at a different path and use an `http-snippet` to override the `opentelemetry_config` directive, or use an init container to copy the file instead. Let me revert the volume mount and explore using a snippet to point to a different location for the config file.\n\nActually, I'm realizing that `opentelemetry_config` is an http-level directive in the generated nginx.conf, so if I try to override it with `http-snippet`, the second directive might conflict with the first one since nginx doesn't allow duplicate directives in the same block.\n\nLet me explore a different approach using environment variables instead.\n\nThe otel_ngx_module documentation mentions that OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT can be set via an environment variable, which means I could use the `env` directive in the main nginx block to expose it. If I add `env OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT;` through the main-snippet and set the variable in the Deployment, the module should pick it up without needing a second `opentelemetry_config` directive. the `env` directive only inherits existing environment variables, it doesn't set them. So my best approach is to set the `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` env var directly in the Deployment, add the `env` directive to the ConfigMap so