nfiguration.\n\nIf the TOML is written at startup with defaults before the ConfigMap is even watched, that would explain why the host is empty—it was baked in before the ConfigMap values could be applied. But then how are the sampler settings matching my ConfigMap exactly? That suggests the TOML IS being generated from the ConfigMap somehow, which contradicts the empty host value.\n\nActually, I think I've got it—those sampler settings happen to match the defaults, not my ConfigMap. The TOML is generated once at startup with defaults and never updated, while the ConfigMap settings get applied through the nginx.conf instead, like the `enable-opentelemetry` directive and log format keys.\n\nBut the collector host only lives in the TOML, not in nginx.conf, so it should be read from the ConfigMap at startup. The new pod should've picked up the updated ConfigMap value, unless the controller is structured in a way where the TOML generation happens before the ConfigMap is actually read, or there's some other timing issue I'm missing. Let me try restarting the pod again and checking the TOML right away to see what's actually there.\n\nActually, I think I've been overcomplicating this. What if I just use an init container to write the correct TOML to an emptyDir volume before the main container starts? That way I can bypass the ConfigMap mounting issue entirely and ensure the TOML has the right values from the start.\n\nBut then I'm back to the same problem—if the controller writes the TOML during its startup sequence before reading the ConfigMap, my init container's file would just get overwritten anyway.\n\nLooking at the actual behavior, the sampler settings in the TOML match my ConfigMap, but the host is empty. That suggests the controller is reading the ConfigMap for some settings but not others, or there's a timing issue where the host gets set to empty after the sampler settings are applied. The TOML is being generated with default values at pod startup, so the ConfigMap settings aren't making it into the TOML file even though they're being applied to nginx.conf. This suggests either a race condition during TOML generation, or the ConfigMap values for those specific OpenTelemetry settings happen to match the defaults, making it impossible to tell if they're actually being applied.\n\nLet me verify what the actual defaults are for the sampler settings—if `AlwaysOn` isn't the default, then my ConfigMap IS being applied to the TOML, which means the `opentelemetry-collector-host` is being set to empty string despite my configuration. I should check if there's a difference in how the host key is processed compared to other keys, or if there's validation logic that might be rejecting non-empty hosts. Looking at the ingress-nginx 1.14.x ConfigMap reference to see what the actual OpenTelemetry keys are. Looking at the default sampler ratio value to understand if my ConfigMap setting is actually being applied, or if I'm just seeing the default behavior. I think the most reliable fix is to revert the broken Deployment patch and instead add an `OTEL_EXPORTER_OTLP_ENDPOINT` environment variable directly, then update the ingress-nginx ConfigMap with a main snippet to expose that variable to nginx.\n\nThe module's TOML documentation explicitly mentions this env var as an alternative, so this approach should work. Since the task requires both trace IDs in logs AND actual trace export to the collector, I need to fix the host configuration—an empty host would fail to connect and prevent trace export entirely. Let me proceed with setting up the environment variable approach. telemetry` with an emptyDir instead, so the controller can write the TOML file there at runtime. That way I avoid the read-only mount issue while still letting the controller generate its config dynamically. I'm realizing the env var approach has its own complications—nginx workers need the `env` directive in the config to actually read environment variables, so I can't just 